You are a senior C++ software engineer.

I want you to implement an RVC(Robotic Vacuum Cleaner) software controller project based on the following requirements.

The project must be implemented as a C++ project with GoogleTest-based unit/system tests and GitHub Actions-based CI/CD.

============================================================
1. Project Goal
============================================================

Develop a software controller for an RVC that automatically cleans and mops household surfaces.

The focus is only on the automatic cleaning behavior of the controller.
Do not implement detailed hardware-level motor control, sensor drivers, or real embedded control logic.
Instead, abstract hardware-related behavior through interfaces or simulation objects.

The final project should include:

- C++ source code
- RVC controller logic
- Sensor/environment abstraction
- Simulator for system testing
- GoogleTest-based tests
- GitHub Actions CI pipeline
- Clear project structure and build instructions

============================================================
2. Core Functional Requirements
============================================================

The RVC controller must support the following behaviors.

[FR-1] Automatic Cleaning
- The RVC automatically cleans and mops a household surface.
- When cleaning starts, the RVC enters an automatic cleaning mode.
- The controller should continuously decide the next action based on sensor/environment input.

[FR-2] Default Movement
- While cleaning, the RVC moves straight forward by default.

[FR-3] Obstacle Avoidance
- If the RVC detects an obstacle in front of it:
  - It stops the current forward movement.
  - It turns either left or right.
  - It continues moving forward while cleaning.

[FR-4] Dead-End Handling
- If obstacles exist in front, left, and right directions:
  - The RVC moves backward.
  - Then it turns either left or right.
  - Then it continues moving forward while cleaning.

[FR-5] Dust Detection
- If the RVC detects dust:
  - It temporarily increases cleaning power.
  - After a short period or a few simulation steps, it returns to normal cleaning power.

[FR-6] Scope Limitation
- Do not implement detailed hardware control.
- Do not implement real motor PWM, real sensor protocols, or embedded device drivers.
- Only model hardware behavior using abstract interfaces, mock objects, or simulator states.

============================================================
3. Future / Extended Requirements to Consider
============================================================

The design should be extensible for the following future requirements, even if they are not fully implemented now.

[ER-1] Sensor Extension
- The RVC may add or change sensors in the future.
- Design sensor handling with interfaces or modular classes.

[ER-2] Spot Circulation Cleaning
- The RVC may support cleaning one spot repeatedly for a while.
- Leave the design open for adding a spot-cleaning behavior or state.

[ER-3] Mobile App Communication
- The RVC may communicate with a mobile app in the future.
- Do not implement the mobile app now.
- But separate controller logic from external command interfaces so that app commands can be added later.

[ER-4] Machine Learning / Inference
- The RVC may use machine learning or inference for more efficient cleaning in the future.
- Do not implement ML now.
- But avoid hard-coding the entire decision logic in a way that prevents future policy replacement.

